00998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Companies &amp; Markets</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">BT EXCLUSIVE; Dual class shares likely to be limited to SGX main board</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>HK and China also in race to accommodate biotech firms and other startups in hope of snaring the next FANG</Para><Para>Singapore</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>WITH China joining the fray to woo back the billions it lost when homegrown startups listed overseas, the battle to list the next FANG (Facebook, Amazon, Netflix, Google) and BAT (Baidu, Alibaba and Tencent) has just become hotter.</Para><Para>By end March, Singapore Exchange (SGX) will publish its response to a consultation issued last year on dual class shares (DCS) - the controversial structure which allows founders and certain shareholders to have higher voting rights or dividends than others. A second consultation on the key framework and rules will be issued at the same time, before they are finalised in time for DCS adoption soon after June.</Para><Para>The Business Times understands that among the proposals will be for companies with DCS to trade on the SGX main board. They must come with safeguards including a sunset clause, where multiple-vote (MV) shares are converted to one-vote (OV) shares under certain circumstances.</Para><Para>In its feedback, CFA Society in Singapore agreed that there should be a sunset clause but suggested SGX should not prescribe a 12-15 year duration.</Para><Para>"The duration should be disclosed at initial public offer (IPO) and any waiver should be decided only by the minority vote. Upon the founding members' demise, permanent incapacity, departure from the company, these MV shares should be converted to OV shares immediately."</Para><Para>When asked about the race among Asian exchanges to be the first to accommodate DCS, SGX chief executive officer Loh Boon Chye said: "Remember the story about the tortoise that wins the race? It is not about being the fastest.''</Para><Para>"It is important to take into account different considerations, just like how we made our adjustments to regulations because there are different segments to cater to. You need to take those back and form a view. Then come out with what suits most of the participants,'' he stressed.</Para><Para>Accommodating DCS is about staying relevant. Singapore's Committee on the Future Economy had identified the share structure to support the growth of high-tech companies.</Para><Para>"Clearly, different companies at different stage of development in different sectors require different kinds of capital structure," Mr Loh said.</Para><Para>"It is easy to define DCS purely from the standpoint of innovative companies, but I think DCS structure really means allowing the brains, the founders, the impactful contribution to the business that lies with a group of people, which typically are the founders, to continue to be able to lead, influence the business strategy even though their economic interests are not with the majority."</Para><Para>Like Singapore, the Hong Kong Stock Exchange (HKEx) is about to upend its strict 30-year adherence to a one-share-one-vote principle, and accommodate DCS and biotech firms without strong records of profitability. HKEx has said DCS firms must be worth at least HK$10 billion (S$1.7 billion) and have annual revenues of at least HK$1 billion. Technology companies with market values of HK$10 billion or more which are already listed elsewhere will be eligible for a secondary listing in Hong Kong under their existing shareholding structure. Biotech firms will be able to list if their expected minimum capitalisation tops HK$1.5 billion.</Para><Para>China, too, has jumped on the bandwagon. It is poised to ease the profitability requirement for IPOs of unicorns from the four sectors of biotechnology, cloud computing, artificial intelligence and advanced manufacturing. Having lost the likes of Alibaba, Tencent and Baidu over the years to overseas exchanges, Chinese authorities are drafting rules and arrangements that will allow these overseas-listed Chinese tech companies to return to the home markets. This will allow mainland investors to trade in these companies which have generated spectacular returns for foreign investors.</Para><Para>Often cited example is Jack Ma's Alibaba Group Holding, which offered its shares at US$68 each in its IPO on the New York Stock Exchange in September 2014. Today, it is trading around US$199 - a staggering 192 per cent spike. Liu Shiyu, chairman of China Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC), the top securities regulator, has lamented these missed opportunities as China's "historical regret".</Para><Para>"Many good companies are developing and the domestic (investors) have not been able to enjoy the fruits and profits of their development. This is a historical regret. Entering the new era, this regret should no longer continue," said Mr Liu.</Para><Para>Now, China is willing to expedite new listings by "unicorn companies" - startups valued at more than US$1 billion - as they shift focus from old economy stocks like properties and banks to high tech firms with cutting edge technologies. It took Foxconn Industrial Internet Co, a unit of Apple's contractor, Foxconn, just 36 days to get its IPO application approved, instead of the standard processing time of several months to years.</Para><Para>According to the South China Morning Post, as many as 500 companies are in the queue, waiting for China's securities regulator to vet their listing applications. Other companies in the pipeline include China's dominant ride-sharing company Didi-Chuxing, the country's biggest on-demand internet service provider Meituan-Dianping, and Ant Financial Services Group, an affiliate of Alibaba.</Para><Para>Executives of tech companies including Baidu Inc and NetEase Inc have expressed interest in listing their shares on China's domestic stock markets as well. Electronics and software company Xiaomi Corp is also mulling a float on both the Chinese mainland and Hong Kong markets.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Angela Tan , Dual class shares likely to be limited to SGX main board </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">"Remember the story about the tortoise that wins the race? It is not about being the fastest.'' - SGX CEO Loh Boon Chye </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

